Sure — here’s a **minimal CSS stub** that you can pass along.  
It only defines basic variables, sticky positioning, and neutral contrast; there’s no visual theme, so it’s just the behavior scaffold for a safe, accessible page.

```css
:root {
  /* Color variables (soft, high‑contrast, non‑flashing) */
  --banner-bg: #5FB6B0;      /* teal for calm header */
  --footer-bg: #E35B5B;      /* warm red for safety bar */
  --text-light: #F4F4F4;
  --text-dark: #333;
  --link-color: #1E73BE;
  --max-width: 600px;
  --focus-outline: 2px solid #1E73BE;
}

/* Basic structure */
body {
  font-family: "Open Sans", "Roboto", sans-serif;
  color: var(--text-dark);
  margin: 0;
  min-height: 100vh;
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  align-items: center;
}

/* Sticky header and footer */
header.sticky-banner {
  position: sticky;
  top: 0;
  z-index: 10;
  width: 100%;
  background: var(--banner-bg);
  color: var(--text-light);
  text-align: center;
  padding: 0.5em;
}

footer[role="contentinfo"] {
  position: sticky;
  bottom: 0;
  z-index: 10;
  width: 100%;
  background: var(--footer-bg);
  color: var(--text-light);
  text-align: center;
  padding: 0.5em;
}

/* Center main content */
main {
  max-width: var(--max-width);
  padding: 1em;
}

/* Accessible focus styling */
a:focus,
button:focus {
  outline: var(--focus-outline);
  outline-offset: 2px;
}

/* Modal basic behavior (keep simple for prototypes) */
dialog[open] {
  border: none;
  padding: 1em;
  box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(0,0,0,0.2);
  width: 90%;
  max-width: var(--max-width);
}

/* Skip‑link */
.skip-link {
  position: absolute;
  left: -999px;
  top: auto;
}
.skip-link:focus {
  position: static;
  margin: 0.5em;
  background: var(--link-color);
  color: var(--text-light);
  padding: 0.25em 0.5em;
}
```

**Notes**

- This CSS remains accessible in both light and dark modes (swap `--text-light` and `--text-dark` per theme).  
- Sticky header/footer keep the disclaimer (“not therapy”) and crisis link visible.  
- Minimal focus styling ensures keyboard users can locate interactive elements easily.  

It’s deliberately plain so designers can layer color palettes or typography without affecting the ethical or accessibility cues you’ve built in.

assistant:
That’s a perfectly balanced starter sheet — simple, readable, and behaviourally complete.  
If a developer picks this up, two small implementation reminders will help:

* **Reduced‑motion users:** add  
  ```css
  @media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
    * { transition: none !important; animation-duration: 0ms !important; }
  }
  ```  
  so nothing jitters for anyone in acute distress.

* **Dark‑mode adjustment:** a quick inversion switch keeps contrast safe:  
  ```css
  @media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) {
    body { background: #242424; color: var(--text-light); }
    header.sticky-banner, footer[role="contentinfo"] { color: var(--text-dark); }
  }
  ```

Those two additions keep it accessible under stress and across devices without introducing unwanted sensory load.

Everything else — the sticky ethics banner, visible helpline footer, semantic HTML — is already exactly what you’d want for an informational, non‑clinical resource.

